"""
MKT Context Commentary — 2 Chronicles chapters 1–5
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2chronicles-1-5.py

Ch 1: Solomon at Gibeon — the dream, the wisdom request
  - Gibeon held the tabernacle + Bezalel's bronze altar (not Nob or Shiloh)
  - Dream theophany at a sanctuary: standard ANE divine-revelation pattern
  - Wisdom request: ANE kingship-wisdom ideology; mirrors Instruction of Amenemope
  - Kue (Cilicia) as the horse-supply region; Egypt as the chariot source

Ch 2: Temple preparations — Phoenician alliance, labor organization
  - Huram of Tyre: the Phoenician cedar-and-expertise alliance (standard for regional builders)
  - The agricultural payment (wheat, barley, oil, wine): standard ANE commodity trade
  - Huram-abi: the mixed Tyrian-Israelite craftsman (mother from Israel, father from Tyre)
  - The foreign-resident census: 153,600 aliens classified by type

Ch 3: Temple construction — dimensions, location, furnishings
  - Mount Moriah: the convergence of Abraham-Isaac (Gen 22:2) and Ornan's threshing floor
  - Temple dimensions (60×20×30): twice the tabernacle in each direction
  - The cherubim (10 cubits tall, 20-cubit wingspan): ANE karibu as divine guardians
  - Named pillars (Jachin and Boaz): attested in Phoenician and Syrian temple architecture

Ch 4: Temple furnishings — the bronze sea, lavers, lampstands
  - The molten sea: cosmic-ocean symbolism (tehom), 12 oxen facing four compass points
  - Ten lavers, ten lampstands, ten tables: the tripling of tabernacle furniture
  - Huram-abi's finished metalwork in the Jordan clay ground

Ch 5: Ark transfer and glory — Sukkot context, cloud fills house
  - Seventh month (Tishri) chosen: the most sacred month, Sukkot setting
  - Only the two tablets in the ark: against traditions that added Aaron's rod + manna jar
  - The Levitical choir and the Shekinah: the tabernacle-inauguration glory (Exod 40) repeated
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p>The Chronicler's post-exilic audience (ca. 400-350 BCE) would read this verse against their present political reality: they lived under Persian imperial rule with no Davidic king. Solomon's establishment (<em>waYYitḥazeQ</em>) &lsquo;over his kingdom&rsquo; thus functions as theological encouragement — the Davidic dynasty was established by YHWH&rsquo;s presence, not merely by political skill. The Chronicler&rsquo;s opening formula &lsquo;YHWH his God was with him and greatly exalted him&rsquo; is the same formula applied to the ideal king throughout the Chronicler&rsquo;s work (1 Chr 11:9 for David; 2 Chr 17:3 for Jehoshaphat). For the post-exilic reader, this was not history but promise: if YHWH exalted Solomon, the same God could restore the Davidic line.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s address &lsquo;to all Israel&rsquo; is a deliberately all-inclusive formula in Chronicles. The post-exilic Chronicler understood &lsquo;all Israel&rsquo; to include the tribes of both former kingdoms — his audience included those whose ancestors had been from both Judah and (via the northern exile) the other tribes now mixed into the Diaspora and return communities. The leaders summoned — commanders of thousands and hundreds, judges, princes, and heads of patriarchal houses — constitute the full governmental and social hierarchy of Israel. The gathering at Gibeon is framed as a national covenant-assembly, not merely a royal religious act.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Gibeon (modern el-Jib, ~9 km northwest of Jerusalem) held a special cultic status in early Israel. The Chronicler states explicitly (1 Chr 16:39; 21:29; 2 Chr 1:3,5) that Bezalel&rsquo;s bronze altar from the Mosaic tabernacle was located there — not at Shiloh or Nob, the previous ark-sites. The tabernacle itself had been at Gibeon since at least the Saulide period. The distinction between Gibeon (tabernacle + bronze altar) and Jerusalem (ark in David&rsquo;s tent, 1 Chr 16:1) meant that legitimate sacrifice required visiting Gibeon, where the Mosaic worship apparatus was located. This explains why Solomon&rsquo;s enormous sacrifice was not at the Jebusite threshing floor or in Jerusalem but at Gibeon — it was the only legitimate altar site.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Chronicler parenthetically notes that David had moved the ark to Jerusalem &lsquo;to the place David had prepared for it&rsquo; — a tent on Zion (1 Chr 15-16). This geographical distinction is theologically important: the ark (YHWH&rsquo;s throne) was in Jerusalem, but the Mosaic tabernacle and bronze altar were at Gibeon. The tension between ark-worship in Jerusalem and Mosaic sacrifice at Gibeon was a unique feature of the early Davidic period. Solomon&rsquo;s temple project will unite both: the ark will finally have a permanent home in Jerusalem with the proper altar and worship apparatus.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The bronze altar at Gibeon is identified as Bezalel&rsquo;s altar — the altar Bezalel son of Uri son of Hur had made (Exod 31:1-5; 38:1-2), constructed during the Sinai wilderness period. That it still existed at Gibeon 400+ years after Moses underscores the continuity of the Mosaic cultic tradition: the very altar on which Israel sacrificed at Sinai was still in use at the inauguration of Solomon&rsquo;s reign. The Chronicler&rsquo;s point is that Solomon, by sacrificing at Bezalel&rsquo;s altar, was operating within the legitimate Mosaic worship tradition rather than innovating independently. The phrase &lsquo;Solomon and the assembly sought YHWH there&rsquo; (<em>ḏāraš</em>, to inquire/seek YHWH at a sanctuary) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s signature term for legitimate worship practice.</p>",
    "6": "<p>One thousand burnt offerings on a single occasion marked Solomon as a king of extraordinary ritual generosity. In ANE royal inscriptions, the extravagance of a king&rsquo;s sacrifice was a mark of piety and legitimacy — Assurnasirpal II&rsquo;s palace dedication inscription records 1,000 fattened head of cattle and vast quantities of grain at his inaugural feast; Nebuchadnezzar II records lavish temple gifts to Marduk. Solomon&rsquo;s thousand burnt offerings at Gibeon establish him as a king of the highest ANE religious prestige. The Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic audience would have understood this as demonstrating that YHWH&rsquo;s temple, though small compared to Nebuchadnezzar&rsquo;s Esagila, was built by a king whose devotion exceeded that of Babylon&rsquo;s kings.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The dream theophany at night following a massive sacrifice at a sanctuary is precisely the form of divine communication expected in ANE religious practice. Gudea of Lagash (ca. 2100 BCE) received instructions to build the Eninnu temple through a dream at the temple precinct; the Egyptian Dream Stele of Thutmose IV records YHWH&rsquo;s Near Eastern equivalent receiving a divine commission in a dream at the Sphinx; the Ugaritic Keret epic begins with El speaking to the distressed king in a dream. Dream-oracles at sacred sites (incubation oracles) were the standard channel for divine revelation to kings in the ancient world. Solomon&rsquo;s Gibeon dream fits this pattern exactly: he sacrificed lavishly, which was understood as an invitation for divine response, and YHWH appeared in the night.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s appeal to &lsquo;your great covenant-loyalty to my father David&rsquo; is the foundational language of the Davidic covenant theology. The Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic audience knew this language from the Psalms (Ps 89 is essentially a meditation on this <em>ḥesed</em> to David in the face of apparent failure). Solomon grounds his prayer in the prior covenant commitment, not in his own merit — the standard ANE approach of appealing to divine steadfast loyalty rather than human deserving. The acknowledgment &lsquo;you have made me king in his place&rsquo; is the covenant succession language: YHWH&rsquo;s appointment, not merely political inheritance.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The comparison between Solomon&rsquo;s people and &lsquo;the dust of the earth&rsquo; (<em>ʿapar hāʾāreṣ</em>) for multitude was the standard ANE hyperbole for an enormous army or nation. The same image appears in the patriarchal promises (Gen 13:16; 28:14) — YHWH will make your offspring &lsquo;as the dust of the earth.&rsquo; Solomon&rsquo;s use of it in prayer acknowledges that his situation is the fulfillment of the Abrahamic promise: Israel is already as numerous as the dust. The problem is governing this vast covenant people, not doubting the promise. This grounds Solomon&rsquo;s wisdom request in covenant-fulfillment: the people are so numerous that wisdom is required to steward what YHWH has already given.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s request for wisdom (<em>ḥokmāh</em>) and knowledge (<em>daʿat</em>) rather than wealth, honor, or military victory is ideologically resonant both within Israel and in the wider ANE. The Egyptian Instruction of Amenemope (ca. 1100 BCE), the Instruction of Ptahhotep, and the Babylonian Counsels of Wisdom all prize practical wisdom as the highest kingly quality. In Egyptian royal ideology, the ideal king was the embodiment of <em>Ma'at</em> (justice/order); his ability to govern was inseparable from his wisdom. Solomon&rsquo;s choice of wisdom over power is the ANE ideal of the good king articulated within YHWH-covenant categories. The pairing of <em>ḥokmāh</em> + <em>daʿat</em> in Chronicles (vs. just &lsquo;understanding heart&rsquo; in 1 Kgs 3:9) emphasizes both practical skill and intellectual knowledge.</p>",
    "11": "<p>YHWH&rsquo;s evaluation of Solomon&rsquo;s request — that he did not ask for wealth, possessions, honor, or military victory — reveals the theological presupposition that these goods belong to a lower order of value than wisdom for governance. In ANE royal ideology, military victory was typically the primary divine gift sought: Mesopotamian kings prayed for the gods to grant them &lsquo;victory over enemies&rsquo; (<em>nashpatum</em>) as the primary blessing. Solomon&rsquo;s refusal to prioritize military gifts and his request for governing wisdom marks a distinctive theological emphasis that the Chronicler found worth repeating: the ideal Davidic king governs by wisdom rather than conquers by force.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The divine counter-gift — wisdom and knowledge, plus wealth, possessions, and honor &lsquo;such as no king before or after&rsquo; had — follows the typical ANE pattern of the divine gift exceeding the request. In the ANE, the gift beyond the request signals extraordinary divine favor. The formula &lsquo;no king before or after&rsquo; is a superlative honor declaration attested in ANE royal inscriptions where kings claim unprecedented divine favor. For the Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic audience, this divine grant to Solomon — unprecedented in human history — is the warrant for the temple itself: a king uniquely gifted with wisdom and resources is uniquely equipped to build YHWH&rsquo;s house.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s return from Gibeon to Jerusalem to stand before the ark marks the completion of the pre-temple phase of his reign. Gibeon (tabernacle) and Jerusalem (ark) have been the two sacred poles of the early Davidic period; now Solomon returns from the legitimate sacrifice-site to the ark&rsquo;s location, and his reign begins in earnest. The sequencing is significant for the Chronicler&rsquo;s audience: even the greatest wisdom and resources require proper worship infrastructure — Gibeon first, then Jerusalem, then the temple project.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s chariot and cavalry force reflects the geopolitical reality of the early Iron Age II (ca. 970-930 BCE). Chariot warfare was the dominant military technology of the period; major powers maintained chariot forces in the hundreds to thousands. Egyptian records from Thutmose III and Ramesses II describe chariot armies in the thousands at battles like Megiddo and Qadesh. Solomon&rsquo;s 1,400 chariots and 12,000 horsemen places him among the significant military powers of the eastern Mediterranean. Megiddo, Tell el-Hesi, and other sites show archaeological evidence of large stable complexes from the Solomonic period. The Chronicler notes these forces without moral evaluation — unlike Deuteronomy 17:16-17&rsquo;s warnings about excessive horses and foreign alliances.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The rhetorical statement that &lsquo;silver and gold were as common in Jerusalem as stones, and cedar was as plentiful as the sycamore figs of the Shephelah&rsquo; is the conventional ANE hyperbole of abundance used in royal inscriptions. The Annals of Assurnasirpal II (879 BCE) describe his palace as overflowing with gold, silver, and bronze &lsquo;like grass.&rsquo; Nebuchadnezzar&rsquo;s inscription about Babylon uses similar abundance formulas. The rhetorical goal is to establish the Solomonic kingdom as a golden age of unparalleled prosperity. The comparison of cedar (expensive Phoenician import) to sycamore-figs (the common fruit-wood of the Judean foothills) effectively communicates that what was elsewhere rare and precious was in Solomon&rsquo;s Jerusalem as ordinary as local wood.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Kue (Hebrew <em>qôʾ</em>) is the ancient name for Cilicia (modern southeastern Turkey), which was the primary horse-breeding region of the ancient Near East in the first millennium BCE. Egyptian records and Assyrian administrative texts confirm that Cilicia/Kue was a major supplier of horses to the region. The &lsquo;king&rsquo;s merchants&rsquo; who collected from Kue represent Solomon&rsquo;s participation in the international horse trade — the Late Bronze Age and Iron Age horse trade ran from the steppes of Anatolia and Central Asia down through Cilicia into the Levant and Egypt. The price given (150 shekels per horse) can be cross-referenced with Assyrian price lists for horses, which run in a similar range for premium animals.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Chariots from Egypt at 600 shekels each reflects the international arms trade of the Iron Age. Egypt was famous for its chariot manufacture — Egyptian chariots of the New Kingdom period were technological marvels of lightweight wood, leather, and bronze construction, superior to Hittite and Canaanite equivalents. Solomon&rsquo;s role as an intermediary — buying chariots from Egypt and horses from Kue and re-exporting them to the Hittite and Aramean kings — describes a genuine trade entrepôt function. Israel&rsquo;s geographic position between Egypt and Mesopotamia made it a natural transit point for the luxury goods (and military hardware) trade. This trading role confirms that Solomon&rsquo;s kingdom was fully integrated into the international commercial network of the early first millennium BCE.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>The dual building project — a house for YHWH&rsquo;s name and a palace for himself — reflects the standard ANE pattern of royal temple-building. Mesopotamian kings routinely built temples and palaces as twin construction projects: the Assyrian kings Shalmaneser I and Tukulti-Ninurta I both built royal temples and palaces together at new capital cities. In ANE royal ideology, the king served as the earthly steward of the national god&rsquo;s temple, so the temple-palace complex was the natural center of royal power. Solomon&rsquo;s version places the house for YHWH&rsquo;s name first (before the palace), which the Chronicler highlights as the appropriate priority.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The labor force numbers — 70,000 burden-bearers, 80,000 stone-cutters, 3,600 supervisors — are consistent with large-scale ANE building projects. Cuneiform administrative texts from Ur III (ca. 2100 BCE) and Neo-Assyrian records document similar numbers of conscripted laborers for royal construction. The quarrying of stone required massive organized labor: the large limestone and sandstone blocks of the temple required extraction, dressing, and transport from the hill country quarries to Jerusalem. The differentiation between three labor categories reflects the administrative sophistication of the Solomonic state.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The diplomatic letter to Huram king of Tyre (the Chronicler&rsquo;s spelling; 1 Kings uses &lsquo;Hiram&rsquo;) invokes the existing trade relationship David had established. Tyre was the dominant commercial power of the eastern Mediterranean in the 10th-9th centuries BCE. Phoenician cedar from Lebanon was the premier building material of the ancient world — both Egypt and Mesopotamia imported it regularly. The cedar trade was so significant that Assurnasirpal II boasted in his Annals that &lsquo;I received tribute from the kings of the seacoast — cedar and beams of cedar, and trees of all kinds.&rsquo; Solomon&rsquo;s appeal to the prior David-Huram relationship follows standard ANE diplomatic protocol: international agreements were framed as personal relationships between kings, extended to their successors.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s theological rationale for building — to provide a place for incense, the bread of the Presence, the regular burnt offerings, the Sabbaths, new moons, and appointed festivals — describes the standard Israelite cultic calendar (Num 28-29). The reference to the incense (<em>qeṭōret sammîm</em>, spiced incense), the bread of the Presence (the twelve loaves changed weekly, Lev 24:5-9), and the regular burnt offerings structures the temple as the space for the national liturgical calendar. The Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic audience, who had resumed temple worship after the return, would recognize this as the description of their own restored practice — connecting Solomonic practice to their present situation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&lsquo;The house I am about to build will be great, because our God is greater than all other gods&rsquo; — Solomon&rsquo;s rhetorical acknowledgment of YHWH&rsquo;s superiority in a letter to a Gentile king is a remarkable piece of missionary diplomacy. In the ANE, temple-building was inseparable from advertising the greatness of the god being honored — the temple&rsquo;s magnificence was a statement about the god&rsquo;s power. The Karnak temple complex, Esagila in Babylon, and the great temples of Ugarit all functioned as architectural proclamations of divine greatness. Solomon frames the temple project in these universal terms — but then immediately adds the transcendence critique of v6.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&lsquo;But who is able to build him a house, since heaven, even the highest heaven, cannot contain him?&rsquo; — this is the critical theological check on all ANE temple ideology. The surrounding cultures treated the temple as the literal dwelling of the god — the inner sanctuary housed the divine statue, which was the embodied presence of the deity (bathed, fed, clothed, and put to bed daily in temple rituals). Solomon&rsquo;s explicit denial of this — YHWH cannot be contained even by the highest heaven, let alone a building — represents a decisive theological departure from ANE temple ideology. The temple is built not to contain YHWH but to provide a place where his people can burn incense before him.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s request for a master craftsman skilled in gold, silver, bronze, iron, purple, crimson, and blue yarns, and experienced in engraving — reflects the full range of luxury materials used in ancient temple construction and decoration. The combination of metalwork, weaving/dyeing, and engraving skills represents the three primary decorative arts of the ancient temple: metal furnishings, textile hangings, and carved stone/wood decoration. The specific mention of purple, crimson, and blue — Phoenician dye products made from murex sea-snails (Murex brandaris and Murex trunculus) — places this firmly in the Phoenician luxury trade. Tyrian purple was the most expensive dye in the ancient world; its mention here signals the highest quality of materials.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Cedar of Lebanon, cypress (&lsquo;algum&rsquo; trees), and algum/sandalwood were the three premium building timbers of the ancient world. Lebanese cedar (<em>Cedrus libani</em>) was the primary structural timber for ancient palaces and temples — its density, resistance to rot, and aromatic quality made it ideal. The Phoenician timber trade was one of the most significant commercial enterprises of the Bronze and Iron Ages: Egyptian records from the Old Kingdom through the New Kingdom document regular shipments of cedar from the Byblos-Lebanon coast. The &lsquo;servants&rsquo; skilled in cutting Lebanon timber were the Phoenician woodcutters whose expertise in mountain forestry and log transport to the coast was legendary in the ancient world.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Solomon requests &lsquo;plenty of timber, because the house I am about to build must be great and wonderful&rsquo; — the prestige of a royal building project was measured in part by the quality and quantity of its imported materials. The Neo-Assyrian kings advertised their building projects by listing the exotic timbers used: Assurnasirpal II&rsquo;s Nimrud palace inscription lists cedar, cypress, juniper, box-tree, mulberry, pistachio, and tamarisk among the timbers used. Solomon&rsquo;s timber request thus follows the standard royal building-project protocol of demonstrating magnificence through imported luxury materials.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s payment offer — 20,000 cors of wheat, 20,000 cors of barley, 20,000 baths of wine, and 20,000 baths of oil — was the standard ANE method of settling international accounts before coinage. Commodity payment was the universal medium of exchange in the Bronze and Iron Ages; the great trading systems of the ancient Near East operated on exchange of agricultural surpluses for timber, metals, and manufactured goods. Israel&rsquo;s comparative advantage was grain and oil (the Galilee and Jezreel Valley were productive agricultural zones) while Phoenicia&rsquo;s was timber and craft skills — making this a natural exchange arrangement.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Huram&rsquo;s reply (&lsquo;because YHWH loves his people he has made you king over them&rsquo;) is a striking instance of Gentile theological recognition of YHWH&rsquo;s sovereignty. The ANE diplomatic convention of acknowledging the great god of a treaty partner (as seen in the Amarna letters, where kings recognize the gods of their counterparts) here produces a Phoenician king&rsquo;s endorsement of the Davidic theology. Whether Huram genuinely believed this or was practicing diplomatic courtesy is not stated; the Chronicler presents it as a Gentile king&rsquo;s witness to YHWH&rsquo;s covenant relationship with Israel.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Huram&rsquo;s blessing of &lsquo;YHWH, God of Israel, maker of heaven and earth&rsquo; is the full creator-title used in the patriarchal narratives (Gen 14:19-20: Melchizedek blessing Abram in the name of &lsquo;El Elyon, maker of heaven and earth&rsquo;). A Gentile king using this title reflects the same pattern as Melchizedek — non-Israelite recognition of Israel&rsquo;s God&rsquo;s universal sovereignty. The Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic audience lived under Persian rule and would have found resonance here: Cyrus&rsquo;s decree also acknowledges YHWH as the God of heaven who commissioned the temple rebuilding (2 Chr 36:23; Ezra 1:2). Gentile recognition of YHWH is part of the Chronicler&rsquo;s theology of universal divine sovereignty.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Huram&rsquo;s offer of &lsquo;Huram-abi&rsquo; (my lord&rsquo;s Huram, a respectful title meaning &lsquo;Huram, master craftsman&rsquo;) is a skilled craftsman of Phoenician-Israelite heritage. The description of his skills — working with gold, silver, bronze, iron, stone, timber, purple, blue, crimson, fine linen, engraving, and any design assigned — matches almost exactly the description of Bezalel&rsquo;s skills for the tabernacle (Exod 31:3-5: filled with wisdom, understanding, and knowledge in every kind of craft). The Chronicler presents Huram-abi as the Solomonic equivalent of Bezalel, providing the master craftsman for the permanent temple as Bezalel had for the portable sanctuary.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Huram-abi&rsquo;s maternal descent from a Danite woman (here; 1 Kgs 7:14 says his mother was from Naphtali — the Chronicler follows a different genealogical tradition) and Tyrian father parallels Bezalel&rsquo;s descent from Judah. In both cases, the craftsman of the sacred space has lineage connecting him to Israel while having access to the finest available craft traditions. The mixed heritage of Huram-abi was entirely plausible in the Iron Age Levant, where intermarriage between coastal Phoenicians and inland Israelites occurred in the border regions of Dan, Naphtali, and Asher. The artisanal tradition he represents — a fusion of Phoenician technical expertise and Israelite covenantal context — mirrors the temple project itself: the finest materials and skills from the surrounding world, dedicated to YHWH.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Huram confirms the payment terms Solomon proposed and undertakes to ship the timber by sea (floating logs down the coast in rafts) to Joppa (the nearest Mediterranean port to Jerusalem). The log-raft technique on the Lebanese coast is attested in Egyptian reliefs from the New Kingdom and in the annals of Tiglath-Pileser I (ca. 1114 BCE), who describes floating cedar logs from Lebanon to Assyria by river. The overland transport from Joppa to Jerusalem (approximately 50 km uphill) would then have been Solomon&rsquo;s responsibility. The port of Joppa would become the landing point for all the imported timber needed for the temple construction.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The census of foreign residents (<em>gērîm</em>, aliens/sojourners) in Israel at 153,600 reflects the demographic reality of post-conquest Canaan, where significant pre-Israelite populations remained in the land (cf. Josh 9: the Gibeonites; the Jebusites in Jerusalem; the non-expelled Canaanite groups of Judges 1). The Chronicler&rsquo;s parallel passage in 1 Chr 22:2 describes David as the one who first conscripted these foreign residents for the temple project. The system of classifying foreign residents by labor type mirrors Mesopotamian administrative practice, where foreign workers (often captured populations or immigrant laborers) were organized into work brigades by skill category.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The 3,600 supervisors (vs. 3,300 in 1 Kgs 5:16 — a different accounting of the supervisory tiers) reflects the managerial infrastructure required for a project of this scale. ANE building projects of similar magnitude — Sargon II&rsquo;s new capital of Dur-Sharrukin, or Nebuchadnezzar&rsquo;s fortification of Babylon — required elaborate administrative hierarchies to coordinate labor, materials, and logistics. The division of the workforce into burden-bearers (transport), quarry workers (extraction), and supervisors (management) reflects the three-tier labor organization standard in ancient large-scale construction.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The allocation of supervisory responsibility (3,600 overseers over the 150,000 foreign workers) gives a ratio of approximately 1 supervisor per 42 workers — consistent with what modern scholars estimate for ANE labor management on large building projects. The 3,300 vs. 3,600 discrepancy between 1 Kings and Chronicles may reflect different accounting periods (pre-project vs. during construction) or different classification systems for the supervisory tiers. For the Chronicler&rsquo;s audience, the organizational detail demonstrates that the temple was built under proper administrative control, not chaotically — another aspect of Solomon&rsquo;s wisdom expressed in practical governance.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p>The Chronicler&rsquo;s explicit identification of the temple site as &lsquo;Mount Moriah&rsquo; (and its connection to the place where YHWH appeared to David at Ornan&rsquo;s threshing floor) is unique in biblical literature and theologically momentous. Genesis 22:2 identifies the &lsquo;land of Moriah&rsquo; as where Abraham was commanded to offer Isaac — the same word (<em>môriyyāh</em>). Whether the Chronicler is making a deliberate identification (these are the same place) or a geographical coincidence is debated by scholars, but the Chronicler clearly intends the reader to recognize the Abraham-Isaac connection. Jerusalem&rsquo;s temple mount thus stands at the intersection of the three most sacred moments in Israel&rsquo;s early history: Abraham&rsquo;s offering, the divine appearance to David, and the threshing floor purchase that established the temple site.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The second month of Solomon&rsquo;s fourth year corresponds to approximately 966 BCE by standard chronology. The second month (<em>Ziv</em> in the older calendar, later <em>Iyyar</em>) was chosen — the same month that the Israelites departed Sinai (Num 10:11) and that David began his reign in Hebron. The Chronicler does not include the 1 Kings 6:1 reference to 480 years after the Exodus — a chronological marker that has generated extensive scholarly discussion (literal vs. symbolic generation count). The omission may reflect the Chronicler&rsquo;s different chronological scheme or his focus on the Davidic-covenant framework rather than the Mosaic-exodus connection.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The &lsquo;old standard&rsquo; cubit mentioned in the dimensions refers to a cubit of approximately 44.5-45 cm (the standard Bronze Age cubit of about 17.5 inches), as opposed to the shorter &lsquo;common cubit&rsquo; of approximately 38-40 cm used in everyday measurement. The distinction between long and short cubits is attested in Ezekiel 40:5 (&lsquo;a measuring rod of six cubits, each cubit being a cubit and a handbreadth&rsquo;) and is paralleled in Egyptian measurement systems (the royal cubit of 52.4 cm vs. the shorter short cubit). The use of the longer &lsquo;old standard&rsquo; cubit means the temple nave (60×20 cubits by the old standard) was approximately 26.7×8.9 meters.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The vestibule (<em>ûlām</em>) is given a height of 120 cubits in Chronicles, vs. the 30 cubits of 1 Kings 6:3. This is one of the most discussed discrepancies between the parallel accounts; many scholars attribute the 120 in Chronicles to a scribal error (the Chronicler&rsquo;s use of 120 elsewhere for the priests at the dedication, or a dittography of the temple length). The LXX version of 2 Chr 3:4 reads &lsquo;twenty&rsquo; rather than &lsquo;one hundred and twenty,&rsquo; which may reflect the original text. A 120-cubit (53-meter) vestibule would make the porch taller than the nave — architecturally unusual but not impossible (Egyptian pylons often exceeded the height of the building they fronted). The question remains unresolved in scholarship.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The interior of the nave (&lsquo;the greater house&rsquo;) was paneled with fir/juniper wood and overlaid with &lsquo;fine gold&rsquo; decorated with palm trees and chains. The decoration of palm trees (<em>tîmōrôT</em>) was the most common motif in Phoenician and Canaanite-period ivories and wood carvings — the stylized palm appears throughout the &lsquo;Phoenician-style&rsquo; ivory carvings found at Arslan Tash, Nimrud, and Megiddo. The alternation of palm trees and lotus/chain patterns was the dominant decorative vocabulary of Iron Age Levantine luxury art. The chains or lattice-work decoration appears in Proto-Aeolic capitals found at Hazor, Megiddo, and Jerusalem itself. Solomon&rsquo;s temple thus expressed its sacred character through the highest available artistic vocabulary of the ancient Near East.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The temple was decorated with precious stones for beauty — the specific stones are not named here; 1 Chr 29:2 mentions onyx, stones for setting, antimony, and stones of various colors, gold in abundance, silver, bronze, iron, and wood. The use of semi-precious stones in temple decoration was common in ANE sacred architecture: Gudea&rsquo;s Eninnu temple is described in Sumerian hymns as decorated with &lsquo;lapis lazuli and gold&rsquo; and &lsquo;carnelian&rsquo; columns. The gold mentioned here — &lsquo;gold of Parvaim&rsquo; — is unidentified (Parvaim may be a region of Arabia or India known for high-quality gold), but the qualifier signals that the finest available gold was used.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The gold overlay of the house — its beams, thresholds, walls, and doors, with cherubim carved on the walls — represents a staggering commitment of gold. Modern estimates suggest the gold overlay described in these chapters would represent hundreds of tons of gold (though such estimates depend heavily on the thickness of the overlay and the exact area). In ANE terms, the gold-overlaid temple was the supreme expression of a deity&rsquo;s glory: Esagila in Babylon was described in cuneiform texts as &lsquo;Esagil, the house of gleaming gold&rsquo;; Egyptian temples were &lsquo;electrum-bright&rsquo; (gold-silver alloy used for their peaks). The gold overlay was not merely decorative but theological — the house of YHWH shone with the same radiance as the divine glory itself.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The Most Holy Place (inner sanctuary) measured 20×20 cubits — a perfect square, approximately 8.9×8.9 meters. The cubic shape (often assumed to be 20 cubits high as well) gives it the proportions of a perfect cube — the most symbolically complete three-dimensional form, representing cosmic completeness. The overlay of 600 talents of fine gold on the inner sanctuary alone is a staggering figure — the equivalent of approximately 20 metric tons of gold at the lighter talent weight (ca. 30 kg per talent). The gold nails weighing 50 shekels each (one of the few instances where the weight of architectural elements is specified in ancient texts) ground this description in a kind of specific hyper-detail that conveys the extraordinary investment of resources.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The gold nails at 50 shekels each — roughly 575 grams per nail — represent a remarkable specification detail. The use of gold nails (pegs/fasteners) in place of iron or bronze nails in the sacred space extends the gold overlay principle to the fastening elements. This parallels the description of the tabernacle&rsquo;s gold clasps and hooks (Exod 26:6,11; 36:13), where even the connecting elements of the sacred space were made from the prescribed precious material. The fact that these nails are weighed and recorded suggests they were individually inventoried — consistent with the meticulous temple accounting that appears in later post-exilic contexts (Ezra 1:7-11 records the specific count of temple vessels).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The two golden cherubim in the Most Holy Place were additional to the two cherubim already on the ark&rsquo;s cover (Exod 25:18-22). The temple cherubim were giant versions — 10 cubits high each, with a wingspan of 5 cubits per wing, so their combined wingspan spanned the entire 20-cubit width of the inner sanctuary. The cherubim were the most common divine-presence symbols in the ancient Near East: Akkadian <em>karibu</em> (the Semitic cognate of <em>kĕrûḇ</em>) were semi-divine intercessors and guardians stationed at divine thresholds. Cherub-decorated furniture and ivory carvings appear throughout the Iron Age Levant; the &lsquo;throne of cherubim&rsquo; (1 Sam 4:4; Ps 80:1) describes YHWH&rsquo;s invisible throne borne by cherubim — the ark as footstool, the cherubim wings as the throne-back.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The wing arrangement of the temple cherubim — outer wing touching the wall on each side, inner wings touching each other in the center of the house — created a continuous wing-span from wall to wall across the 20-cubit inner sanctuary. This positioning means the ark sat beneath the joined inner wings of the two giant cherubim, as if they were sheltering/enthroning the divine presence. The joining of the inner wings mirrors the cherubim of the ark&rsquo;s cover (Exod 25:20: &lsquo;The cherubim shall spread out their wings above, overshadowing the mercy seat with their wings&rsquo;). The temple&rsquo;s giant cherubim replicate and magnify the ark&rsquo;s cherubim at a monumental scale.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The structural repetition of the wing measurements (v11-12 essentially describe the same configuration from different angles) reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s meticulous concern with the exactness of the sacred space. In ANE building accounts, precise measurement was a religious requirement, not merely a practical one: Gudea&rsquo;s Eninnu temple hymns describe the deity providing exact plans and measurements before construction began; the Assyrian kings documented their building projects with surveys and measurements that the gods were understood to have verified. The Chronicler&rsquo;s repetition of measurements has a similar ritual function: verifying that the sacred proportions were correctly realized.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The cherubim stood &lsquo;with their faces toward the nave&rsquo; — looking outward toward the main hall, where the priests served. This orientation differs from the ark&rsquo;s cherubim (Exod 25:20: &lsquo;facing each other, with their faces toward the mercy seat&rsquo;). The temple cherubim&rsquo;s outward gaze may signify their role as guardians of the threshold between the Most Holy Place and the nave — watching the approach to the divine presence rather than focusing on the ark. In ANE temple iconography, guardian figures (lamassus, lion-gates, cherubim) consistently face outward to monitor and protect the sanctuary entrance.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The veil (<em>pārôkeT</em>) separating the nave from the Most Holy Place was made of the same four materials as the tabernacle veil (Exod 26:31): blue, purple, crimson, and fine twisted linen. The purple and crimson were Phoenician dyes (murex purple and kermes/crimson from insects), representing the most expensive textile colorants available. The woven cherubim on the veil created a textile version of the carved cherubim on the walls — the sacred boundary of the inner sanctuary was marked on every surface (walls, floor, ceiling, and the hanging veil) with cherubim imagery, making the approach to the divine presence a journey through a cherub-guarded threshold.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The two pillars, Jachin (יָכִין, &lsquo;he establishes&rsquo;) and Boaz (בֹּעַז, &lsquo;in him is strength&rsquo;), stood before the temple. Monumental free-standing pillars flanking temple entrances are attested in multiple ANE contexts: at Tell Tayinat (ancient Kunulua in North Syria, ca. 900-800 BCE), a &lsquo;bit hilani&rsquo; palace-temple has two column bases in the exact position described for Jachin and Boaz; similar features appear at Hazor, Tell el-Far'a, and Megiddo temples in the Iron Age Levant. The pillars may have been hollow fire-stands (flaming beacons), or simply monumental markers of the sacred threshold. Their names (divine declarations of stability and power) suggests they functioned as architectural proclamations of YHWH&rsquo;s eternal covenant-keeping.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The chains of the inner sanctuary and the hundred pomegranates on the chains — the pomegranate was the most common decorative motif in Israelite sacred art of the Iron Age. Pomegranate-shaped stone objects and ivory pomegranates appear throughout archaeological contexts from the period; a famous ivory pomegranate (now debated as to authenticity) was once thought to be from the Jerusalem temple. The pomegranate&rsquo;s many seeds made it a symbol of abundance and fertility in the ancient world; its use in temple decoration (also on the hem of the high priest&rsquo;s robe, Exod 28:33-34) connected the sacred space with themes of divine provision and blessing.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The pillar heights of 35 cubits each (vs. 18 cubits in 1 Kgs 7:15 — another Chronicles/Kings discrepancy, perhaps including the capital in the measurement) and the capital heights of 5 cubits atop each pillar. The capitals were decorated with lily-work and networks of pomegranates (described in detail in 1 Kgs 7:18-20). The capitols of Proto-Aeolic type found in archaeological contexts from Iron Age Israelite sites (Megiddo, Hazor, Samaria) show the palm-tree capital design that characterized Israelite monumental architecture of the period. The pillars thus represented the high point of Israelite decorative architectural achievement in the Iron Age.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>The bronze altar of 20×20×10 cubits — roughly 8.9×8.9×4.4 meters — was substantially larger than the tabernacle&rsquo;s bronze altar (Exod 27:1: 5×5×3 cubits, approximately 2.2×2.2×1.3 meters). The dramatic scaling up from the tabernacle to the temple reflects the transition from a portable sanctuary to a permanent national cult center. The size of the altar was directly proportional to the volume of sacrifices it needed to handle: the temple served all Israel&rsquo;s sacrificial needs, not merely a single community&rsquo;s. 1 Kings 7:23 does not describe this altar; it appears first in 1 Kgs 8:64 and is described here by the Chronicler in preparation for the dedication narrative.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The molten sea (<em>yam mûṣāq</em>) was a large bronze basin of 10 cubits diameter and 5 cubits depth with a circumference of 30 cubits — the ratio implies a value of pi slightly above 3.0, which was the standard engineering approximation in the ancient Near East (Babylonian mathematics also used pi ≈ 3 for practical calculations). The capacity of 3,000 baths (2 Chr 4:5) vs. 2,000 baths (1 Kgs 7:26) may reflect the difference between brim-full capacity and working capacity. The sea rested on twelve bronze oxen standing in groups of three facing the four compass points. The cosmic symbolism of the sea was significant in the ANE: the Babylonian <em>apsu</em> (primordial underground freshwater ocean) was represented by a basin of water in the Esagila temple precinct. The Israelite molten sea may symbolize the same concept — the cosmic waters under divine control — but here placed under the care of the twelve tribes (twelve oxen).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The decorative figures of oxen around the base of the sea (ten per cubit around the circumference) were cast as part of the sea structure. The oxen decoration connects the sea to the twelve ox-supports beneath it, creating a unified motif of bovine imagery. In ANE iconography, the bull/ox was the most common symbol of divine strength and fertility — the Canaanite El was depicted as a bull, and Baal was shown standing on a bull. The deliberate use of bull imagery at the base of the bronze sea may represent YHWH&rsquo;s mastery over the cosmic waters (Ps 29:3: &lsquo;The voice of YHWH is over the waters&rsquo;; Ps 74:13: &lsquo;You divided the sea by your might&rsquo;). The temple sea thus celebrates YHWH as the sovereign over creation&rsquo;s waters.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The twelve oxen standing three to each compass point create a directional symbolism: they face the four cardinal directions (north, south, east, west), with three facing each direction. In ANE cosmology, the four compass directions represented the totality of the earth — to have twelve guardian figures facing all four directions suggested protection and authority over the entire world. The twelve may also symbolize the twelve tribes of Israel, with the bronze sea representing the waters of blessing that flow to all twelve through YHWH&rsquo;s provision. The oxen standing, not kneeling — suggesting strength and readiness — and all together supporting the sea create an image of communal Israelite strength sustaining YHWH&rsquo;s sacred space.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The sea&rsquo;s brim made like the brim of a cup, shaped like a lily (<em>šûšan</em>, lotus flower), is a specific decorative element. The lotus or lily was among the most ubiquitous decorative motifs of the ancient Near East and Egypt — it appears in Egyptian capitals, Phoenician ivory carvings, and throughout the decorative arts of Iron Age Canaan. Its use here on the rim of the sea connects the temple&rsquo;s water feature with the broader aesthetic vocabulary of its time. The capacity note — 3,000 baths (Chronicles) vs. 2,000 baths (Kings) — represents a significant discrepancy; modern scholarship has proposed various explanations including different bath measures or different counting methods (interior vs. exterior volume).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The ten lavers (wash basins) for rinsing the parts of burnt offerings represent a major expansion of the tabernacle&rsquo;s single bronze basin (<em>kiyyôr</em>, Exod 30:18-21). The tabernacle&rsquo;s basin was used for priestly hand-and-foot washing; the temple&rsquo;s ten lavers are specifically for washing the components of the <em>ʿôlāh</em> (burnt offering — the legs and entrails required washing before burning, Lev 1:9,13). The scale-up from one basin (tabernacle) to ten lavers + one sea (temple) parallels the scale-up in all temple furnishings. The sea was for the priests&rsquo; own washing; the lavers were for the sacrificial animals. This functional distinction is explicitly stated here and not in 1 Kings.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The ten golden lampstands (five on each side of the nave) represented a fivefold multiplication of the tabernacle&rsquo;s single seven-branched menorah (Exod 25:31-40). Whether these lampstands were also seven-branched (each being a menorah) or simpler stands is not specified, but tradition (cf. Josephus, <em>Antiquities</em> 8.3.7) suggests they were menorot. The seven-branched form of the menorah was cosmologically significant: seven representing the days of creation and the seven visible planets of the ancient world. Ten menorot multiplied this sevenfold symbolism throughout the nave, filling the sacred space with the light of the created order under YHWH&rsquo;s governance.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Ten gold tables (for the bread of the Presence) represent a tenfold multiplication of the tabernacle&rsquo;s single table of showbread (Exod 25:23-30). The twelve loaves of showbread renewed weekly symbolized YHWH&rsquo;s perpetual provision for the twelve tribes. The multiplication to ten tables is not explained functionally — 2 Chr 4:19 clarifies that &lsquo;the tables&rsquo; (plural) held the bread of the Presence, but does not specify how the twelve loaves were distributed across ten tables. The hundred gold bowls (<em>mizrāqôt</em>) were used for sprinkling blood in sacrificial rites — a one-hundredfold multiplication of the tabernacle&rsquo;s bowls suggests the temple was equipped for the full national sacrificial load.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The inner court (for priests) and the great court (for the assembly) are the two main architectural zones of the temple complex. The parallel with the tabernacle (which had a single court surrounding the tent) shows an expansion into nested sacred zones: the inner sanctuary (Most Holy Place) → the nave (Holy Place) → the inner court (priests) → the great court (laity). This multi-zone structure appears in ANE temple complexes: Mesopotamian temples typically had nested courtyards of increasing sanctity; Egyptian temple complexes moved from public pylon forecourts through successive sacred enclosures to the inner sanctuary (naos). The Solomonic temple complex participates in this ANE pattern of gradated holiness.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The bronze sea was placed on the right (south) side of the temple complex, southeast specifically. The cardinal placement of the sea at the southeastern corner of the inner court positioned it where the priests would encounter it as they entered from the southern approach to perform their ritual purification before entering the sanctuary. The sea&rsquo;s position &lsquo;toward the east&rsquo; and &lsquo;toward the south&rsquo; matches the general Solomonic temple orientation: the temple faced east, so its south side was the right side from the perspective of the worshiper entering from the east.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The summary of Huram-abi&rsquo;s completed metalwork — the pots, shovels, and bowls — constitutes the practical utensils of the sacrificial system. The pots (<em>sîrôT</em>) removed ashes from the altar; the shovels (<em>yaʿîm</em>) were for moving coals and ash; the bowls (<em>mizrāqôT</em>) collected and dashed sacrificial blood. These items represented the daily operational equipment of the altar service — less glamorous than the architectural elements but essential to the functioning of the cult. Their casting in bronze by Huram-abi completes the craftsman&rsquo;s contract: from the architectural elements (sea, pillars, lavers) to the liturgical vessels (pots, shovels, bowls).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The pillars, the two bowl-shaped capitals atop them, the networks and pomegranate decorations, the lavers, and the sea — this summary catalogue of Huram-abi&rsquo;s completed work parallels the tabernacle summaries in Exodus 39-40, where each craftsman&rsquo;s completed work is inventoried before the sanctuary is assembled. The explicit recording of what was made, by whom, and of what material serves the function of an official temple record — the kind of building inscription or temple archive that was standard in ANE royal construction projects. The Assyrian Annals regularly include &lsquo;what I built&rsquo; sections with material inventories; the Sumerian Gudea cylinders list the temple&rsquo;s component parts in similar fashion.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The 400 pomegranates on the two networks (200 per capital) surrounding the two pillar-crowns — the Phoenician decorative motif extended to its maximum expression at the temple entrance. Pomegranates on the high priest&rsquo;s robe hem (Exod 28:33-34; 39:24-26) and on the temple pillar capitals created a visual connection between the priest who entered the sanctuary and the architectural frame through which he passed. The symmetry (200 per capital, two rows per network) suggests a carefully planned decorative program rather than improvised ornamentation — indicating a designed aesthetic vocabulary for the sacred space.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The lavers on their stands (<em>mĕkônôT</em>, moveable bronze bases) are described in detail in 1 Kings 7:27-39 (the &lsquo;ten stands&rsquo; passage), though the Chronicler summarizes briefly. The stands were wheeled bronze carts with decorative panels of lions, oxen, and cherubim — the full range of sacred animal imagery. Their mobility (wheels) within the temple court allowed them to be repositioned as needed. The laver-stands represent a remarkable feat of Bronze Age metalworking: wheeled frames of cast bronze with decorated panels and axle-pin pivots, capable of supporting large water-filled basins. These may be among the most complex metalwork objects ever produced in the Iron Age Levant.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The single molten sea and its twelve ox-supports are summarized again as a unit — the sea and the oxen below it forming one integrated architectural element. The repetition of the sea&rsquo;s description at this point in the summary (after the lavers) may reflect a different organizational logic in the Chronicler&rsquo;s source: the lavers-and-stands as a group followed by the sea-and-oxen as another group, before the summary statement of all the work completed.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The pots, shovels, forks, and all other vessels were made of burnished bronze (&lsquo;shining bronze&rsquo;). The burnishing technique — polishing cast bronze to a mirror-like surface — was a Phoenician specialty attested in the metalwork from Nimrud and Arslan Tash. Shining/polished bronze reflects light dramatically in torch-lit spaces, adding to the luminous quality of the sacred precinct. The attribution of all this work to &lsquo;Huram-abi for King Solomon for the house of YHWH&rsquo; frames the craftsman as the agent of both the king and YHWH — a common ANE pattern where the divine architect (god) uses a human king (patron) and a master craftsman (builder) in a three-party relationship. Gudea served as the builder for Ningirsu through the guidance of the god&rsquo;s dreams; Solomon serves YHWH through Huram-abi&rsquo;s skill.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The clay ground for casting in the Jordan Valley — between Succoth (near the Jabbok River confluence with the Jordan) and Zarethan — identifies the geographic location of the bronze foundry. The Jordan Valley&rsquo;s fine clay deposits were ideal for casting large bronze objects: the clay could be shaped into molds that would withstand the high temperatures of molten bronze. The archaeological site of Tell es-Saʿidiyeh (possibly Zarethan) in the Jordan Valley has yielded evidence of metallurgical activity from the Iron Age. The location in the Jordan rift, away from Jerusalem, kept the industrial processes (including the fuel consumption and smoke) away from the sacred capital.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Solomon made all these vessels in such great quantities that the weight of the bronze was never calculated — the rhetorical hyperbole of uncountable abundance confirms the legendary scale of the temple project in the collective memory. The same formula appears in 1 Kgs 7:47. The &lsquo;uncountable&rsquo; claim was a standard ANE formula of royal abundance: Assyrian inscriptions describe temple dedication gifts as &lsquo;like the dust of the earth&rsquo; or &lsquo;without number.&rsquo; For the Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic audience, the comparison between Solomon&rsquo;s overflowing temple resources and the modest furnishings of the second temple (cf. Hag 2:3: &lsquo;Who among you saw this house in its former glory?&rsquo;) was pointed — but the Chronicler&rsquo;s message was that the same God who filled the first temple with uncountable bronze was present with the restored community.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The gold vessels listed — the altar, the tables with the bread of the Presence, the lampstands (with their lamps) — are the inner sanctuary furnishings contrasting with the outer bronze vessels. The two-material pattern (gold for the sacred interior, bronze for the outer court) consistently marks the gradation of holiness: approaching the Most Holy Place meant approaching increasingly costly and refined materials. The same pattern structured the tabernacle (gold furnishings inside the tent, bronze outside in the courtyard, Exod 25-27). The Chronicler&rsquo;s inventory of both the gold interior and the bronze exterior furnishings thus provides the full picture of the temple&rsquo;s material expression of graduated holiness.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The gold lampstands and their lamps that burned &lsquo;before the inner sanctuary, as prescribed&rsquo; — the technical phrase <em>kammišpaṭ</em> (according to the prescribed manner) invokes the Torah&rsquo;s lamp regulations (Exod 27:20-21; Lev 24:1-4: &lsquo;the lamps shall burn continually before YHWH&rsquo;). The eternal lamp was one of the most symbolically charged elements of Israelite worship — YHWH&rsquo;s presence illuminated by a lamp that burned without ceasing. The transition from the tabernacle&rsquo;s single lamp to the temple&rsquo;s ten lampstands (here described as functioning &lsquo;before the inner sanctuary&rsquo;) multiplied this eternal-light symbolism across the nave.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The flowers, lamps, and golden tongs made of &lsquo;pure gold&rsquo; (<em>zāhāb sāgûr</em>, literally &lsquo;shut/sealed gold,&rsquo; perhaps refined or locked-in gold of the highest purity) represent the finest materials for the innermost sanctuary equipment. The flower decorations on the lampstands were described in detail in Exodus 25:31-40 — the tabernacle menorah had six branches each with three cups shaped like almond flowers. The golden tongs (&lsquo;snuffers&rsquo;) were used to trim the wicks of the lamps without touching them with fingers, maintaining ritual purity in the handling of the sacred fire.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The golden wick-trimmers (snuffers), basins, spoons, and censers complete the inventory of inner sanctuary vessels. The censers (<em>mahTôT</em>, literally &lsquo;fire-pans&rsquo;) were used to carry live coals from the outer altar into the inner sanctuary for the incense burning (Lev 16:12: on the Day of Atonement, the high priest took a censer full of coals &lsquo;from the altar before YHWH&rsquo; into the inner sanctuary). The door specification — the inner doors to the Most Holy Place and the outer doors to the nave were made of gold — extends the gold overlay to the hinges and doorposts themselves, making the transition zones between sacred spaces as richly adorned as the spaces themselves.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>The completion formula &lsquo;all the work Solomon did on the house of YHWH was finished&rsquo; (<em>waTTiSHlem kol-hamMelāʾḵāh</em>) echoes the completion of the tabernacle (Exod 39:32: &lsquo;all the work of the tabernacle of the tent of meeting was finished&rsquo;; Exod 40:33: &lsquo;Moses finished the work&rsquo;). The Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic audience knew the second temple was now standing — the fact that it had been built at all (after the Babylonian destruction) was the miracle. The formula connects the second temple implicitly to both the tabernacle and the first temple: the same YHWH who completed each previous building project was present in the ongoing worship of the restored community.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Solomon summoned all the elders of Israel at the seventh month (Tishri, October-November) — the most sacred month in the Israelite calendar. The seventh month contained Yom Teruʿah (the Feast of Trumpets, Num 29:1), Yom Kippur (the Day of Atonement, Lev 16; 23:26-32), and Sukkot (the Feast of Tabernacles, Lev 23:33-43). The choice of the seventh month for the ark-transfer and temple dedication connected the building&rsquo;s inauguration with Israel&rsquo;s most theologically concentrated season of worship. This timing placed the dedication within the Sukkot festival (vv3, 7:8-10), which was the annual re-enactment of Israel&rsquo;s wilderness pilgrimage — appropriate for the transition from the ark&rsquo;s &lsquo;wilderness-era&rsquo; tent to its permanent house.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The assembly &lsquo;at the feast in the seventh month&rsquo; confirms the Sukkot context. Sukkot was Israel&rsquo;s most joyful and communal festival — a seven-day celebration followed by a solemn eighth-day closing assembly (<em>ʿaṣeret</em>), during which the harvest was completed and Israel remembered the wilderness years. The connection between the wilderness booths (<em>sukkôt</em>) and the temple dedication is theologically apt: the ark had traveled from the wilderness tabernacle to this permanent house; the Sukkot festival celebrated YHWH&rsquo;s provision during that wilderness journey. The all-Israel assembly at the feast is the covenant community gathered at its liturgical peak, the perfect context for YHWH to take up residence in his house.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Levites carried the ark — the Chronicler consistently emphasizes Levitical responsibility for the ark (1 Chr 15:2: &lsquo;no one may carry the ark of God except the Levites&rsquo;; this corrects the Uzzah incident of 2 Sam 6/1 Chr 13 where the ark was carried on a cart). The full retinue of sacred vessels is transferred: &lsquo;all the holy vessels that were in the tent.&rsquo; The phrase &lsquo;the Levites took it up&rsquo; using the specific carrying term (<em>nāśāʾ</em>, to bear/lift up) is the precise term used throughout Numbers for Levitical carrying of the tabernacle components (Num 4). The Chronicler&rsquo;s emphasis on proper Levitical protocols for the ark&rsquo;s transfer reflects the post-exilic community&rsquo;s heightened attention to correct worship procedure.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The simultaneous transfer of the tent of meeting (the tabernacle from Gibeon) and its sacred vessels with the ark closed the gap between the two sacred sites of the Davidic period (Gibeon = tabernacle; Jerusalem = ark). The permanent temple now housed both the ark and the tabernacle&rsquo;s vessels under one roof. The phrase &lsquo;the holy vessels that were in the tent&rsquo; — the bronze altar (Bezalel&rsquo;s altar from Gibeon), the laver, and the utensils — all relocated to Jerusalem. Archaeological evidence for the temple complex suggests a large storage area for such vessels; the &lsquo;treasury rooms&rsquo; described in 1 Kgs 6:5-6 (the side chambers) would have been the repository for this accumulated sacred heritage.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The sacrifices before the ark were so numerous they could not be recorded — sheep and cattle without number. The phrase echoes the same hyperbole used for the bronze vessels (4:18: &lsquo;the weight of the bronze was not calculated&rsquo;). The multiplication of animal sacrifices at moments of covenant inauguration or renewal was standard in the ancient world: at Sennacherib&rsquo;s Nineveh temple dedication, vast numbers of animals are recorded; at the inauguration of the second temple (Ezra 6:17), 100 bulls, 200 rams, 400 lambs, and 12 male goats were offered. Solomon&rsquo;s uncountable sacrifices represent the maximum possible expression of the covenant community&rsquo;s gratitude and dedication at this singular moment.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The priests placed the ark in the inner sanctuary (&lsquo;most holy place&rsquo;, <em>qōḏeš haQqŏḏāšîm</em>), beneath the spread wings of the cherubim — the precise final resting place of the ark was beneath the giant cherubim&rsquo;s wings. The ark was thus simultaneously the footstool of YHWH&rsquo;s invisible throne (1 Chr 28:2; Ps 132:7: &lsquo;let us come to his footstool&rsquo;) and the object sheltered by the cherubim wings. The ark beneath the cherubim&rsquo;s shelter created a multi-layered sacred image: the cherubim on the ark&rsquo;s own cover sheltered the mercy seat; the giant temple cherubim sheltered both the ark and its attending cherubim — a concentric nesting of sacred imagery.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The cherubim&rsquo;s wings spread over both the ark and its poles — the Chronicler specifies that the spread-wings covered the ark&rsquo;s carrying poles. The ark&rsquo;s poles were never to be removed (Exod 25:15: &lsquo;The poles shall remain in the rings of the ark; they shall not be removed from it&rsquo;) — a permanent reminder that the ark was the throne of the God of Israel who led his people on the march. Even in the permanent temple, the poles remained, signaling that YHWH was not permanently domesticated in a fixed location but remained the God who moves with his people. The poles visible &lsquo;from the holy place before the inner sanctuary&rsquo; were visible to the priests performing daily service — a daily reminder of YHWH&rsquo;s pilgrim-nature even in his house.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The poles extended so that their tips were visible from the Holy Place — long enough to be seen through the veil but not long enough to project beyond it. This specific detail about pole-length visible through the veil is a remarkable piece of architectural precision: the poles were long enough to cross the threshold of the veil&rsquo;s spatial boundary without breaking it. The phrase &lsquo;they are there to this day&rsquo; is a documentary formula (<em>ʿaḏ haYYôm hazZeh</em>) indicating that the Chronicler&rsquo;s source preserved a tradition from an eyewitness or near-contemporary period when the temple and its contents were still accessible. After the Babylonian destruction (586 BCE), such a statement could only be a citation from a pre-destruction source.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&lsquo;There was nothing in the ark except the two tablets that Moses placed in it at Horeb&rsquo; — this explicit statement contrasts with later Jewish tradition that the ark also contained the broken first tablets (b. Bava Batra 14b), Aaron&rsquo;s rod (Num 17:10; cf. Heb 9:4), and a jar of manna (Exod 16:33; cf. Heb 9:4). The Chronicler&rsquo;s source (which also appears in 1 Kgs 8:9) insists that only the two tablets of the Decalogue were in the ark at this point. The manna jar and Aaron&rsquo;s rod may have been kept near the ark (Num 17:10 says the rod was placed &lsquo;before the testimony&rsquo;; Exod 16:34 says the manna jar was placed &lsquo;before the testimony&rsquo;) rather than inside it. The two tablets alone in the ark define the ark&rsquo;s essential content: the covenant document, the Decalogue, is the heart of the sacred box.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The unusual detail that &lsquo;all the priests who were present had consecrated themselves, without regard to their divisions&rsquo; indicates that the temple dedication required every available priest, not the regular rotational service (which David had organized into twenty-four divisions, 1 Chr 24). The emergency-assembly of all priests regardless of their divisional rota reflects the extraordinary nature of this liturgical moment — the ark&rsquo;s installation and YHWH&rsquo;s glory-descent required maximum priestly presence. The Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic audience, familiar with the rotational divisions (established by Zerubbabel and Joshua, Ezra 6:18), would recognize the suspension of the normal schedule as a signal of the event&rsquo;s transcendent importance.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Levitical choir — Asaph, Heman, and Jeduthun with their sons and brothers — standing to the east of the altar in fine linen, with cymbals, harps, and lyres, alongside 120 priests with trumpets. This is the full orchestral complement of the temple music: the three great Levitical choir families (the three principal singers David appointed, 1 Chr 15:17-19; 25:1-6) with their complete family-choirs, accompanied by the full trumpet section of the priesthood. The Chronicler&rsquo;s detailed attention to the worship personnel and their instruments reflects his post-exilic community&rsquo;s deep investment in the Levitical music system — the second temple&rsquo;s Levitical singers traced their legitimacy directly to this Davidic/Solomonic appointment.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The moment when the trumpeters and singers made one sound — <em>kĕqôl ʾeḥāḏ</em> (as one voice/sound) — singing &lsquo;for he is good; for his steadfast love endures forever&rsquo; and the cloud filled the house, is the climax of the entire temple-building narrative. The unity of instrumental and vocal praise producing the divine presence-cloud is the most dramatic liturgical moment in Chronicles. The formula &lsquo;for he is good; for his steadfast love endures forever&rsquo; (<em>kî-ṭôḇ kî lĕʿôlām ḥasdô</em>) is the refrain of Ps 136 (repeated 26 times) and appears also in Ps 100:5; 106:1; 107:1; 118:1,29. It was the foundational liturgical formula of the second temple worship — the Chronicler&rsquo;s community sang this refrain at the rebuilt temple (Ezra 3:11). By connecting the formula to YHWH&rsquo;s glory-descent at the first temple&rsquo;s dedication, the Chronicler grounds the second temple&rsquo;s worship in the inaugural moment of YHWH&rsquo;s visible approval.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The cloud filling the temple so that the priests could not stand to minister repeats the tabernacle&rsquo;s dedication (Exod 40:34-35: &lsquo;Moses could not enter the tent of meeting, because the cloud had settled on it and the glory of YHWH filled the tabernacle&rsquo;). The <em>kāḇôḏ</em> (glory) filling the house is the visible, physical manifestation of YHWH&rsquo;s presence — so dense and overwhelming that human service becomes impossible in its immediate presence. The incapacitation of the priests is not judgment but the excess of divine glory over human capacity. For the Chronicler&rsquo;s post-exilic audience, the second temple&rsquo;s dedication did not produce this visible glory (Hag 2:3; Ezek 43:1-5 projects a future glory-return that had not yet occurred). The memory of the first temple&rsquo;s inauguration-glory was thus both a comfort (YHWH&rsquo;s commitment to his house) and an expectation (the greater glory still to come).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(existing, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in CONTEXT.values())
    print(f'2Chronicles 1-5 mkt-context written ({total} verses across 5 chapters).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
